<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-06-20T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-06-20T16:00:00-05:00" n="153" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d153">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/12316:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-06-21T00:00:00+03:00">June
                                        21, 1941—12 a.m.</date>
                                    <lb/> [Received June 21—10:09 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>1190. Lightner<note n="85" xml:id="d153fn85">E. Allan Lightner, Jr.,
                                    Third Secretary of Embassy in the Soviet Union.</note> reports
                                from Vladivostok that while traveling from Krasnoyarsk to Chita his
                                train met between 200 and 220 westbound <pb facs="0163" n="151" xml:id="pg_151"/> trains averaging 25 cars each, of which 7 were
                                loaded with troops and the remaining 18 with artillery, tanks,
                                anti-aircraft searchlight, “knocked down” aircraft and miscellaneous
                                army supplies and equipment. He noted no unusual movement west of
                                Krasnoyarsk nor east of Chita.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>